<div id="review_9376406" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/9376406" />
    <a title="Ginger Lau" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/419215-ginger-lau"><img alt="Ginger Lau" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1195859613p2/419215.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/9376406?book_show_action=true">Nov 20, 2007</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Ginger Lau" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Ginger Lau" href="/user/show/419215-ginger-lau">Ginger Lau</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>


          <div><span class="uitext greyText">Recommends it for: </span>
           <span class="uitext reviewText">Teenagers</span></div>

        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/419215-ginger-lau?shelf=advisory2007-2008">advisory2007-2008</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer9376406" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer4175939845177675161">It&apos;s been a while since I&apos;ve read a realistic fiction YA novel and I was not disappointed by Hard Love. Hard Love is told from the perspective of John, a High School Junior who is incapable of expressing his emotions. He hides behind his journal and his &quot;zine&quot;, Bananafish. Writing is his escape, his only place to be who he is. The reason for his isolation from the world and his enclosed heart is the divorce of his parents. John&apos;s father left his mother and throughout John&apos;s childhood his father </span>
  <span id="freeText4175939845177675161" style="display:none">It's been a while since I've read a realistic fiction YA novel and I was not disappointed by Hard Love. Hard Love is told from the perspective of John, a High School Junior who is incapable of expressing his emotions. He hides behind his journal and his "zine", Bananafish. Writing is his escape, his only place to be who he is. The reason for his isolation from the world and his enclosed heart is the divorce of his parents. John's father left his mother and throughout John's childhood his father was unable to be there by his or his mother's side. John's choice to close off his heart is a reflection of the transition which many teens have to face. John chose to run away -- run away from his true feelings, his true identity, so that he did not have to deal with suffering or pain. I think that it's safe to say that everyone will have that point in their life when it seems like the only solution is "out". Humans are attached to their emotions, and therefore once they cannot rely on their emotions they are helpless. The only way to heal our emotions is to express them, to understand them ourselves, and to never get caught up in throwing away the emotions we have. </span>
  <a data-text-id="4175939845177675161" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


