<div id="review_123953322" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/123953322" />
    <a title="Madisen" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/4258422-madisen"><img alt="Madisen" src="https://s.gr-assets.com/assets/nophoto/user/f_50x66-6a03a5c12233c941481992b82eea8d23.png" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/123953322?book_show_action=true">Sep 29, 2010</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Madisen" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Madisen" href="/user/show/4258422-madisen">Madisen</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer123953322" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer6493259908118891451"> The beginning of the book was ridiculously slow. The plot didn&apos;t pick up until about half way through. The characters didn&apos;t have a stand out personality. They seemed to be those kids that are hiden and shy. <br/><br/>Gio, the alone teenage boy doesn&apos;t really understand the &quot;liking&quot; of the oposite sex, but when he meets Marisol, who in this case is lesbian, he falls in love. Giving the impression that he doesn&apos;t really know what he wants. Marisol is a bit confused as well. She knows that her preference i</span>
  <span id="freeText6493259908118891451" style="display:none"> The beginning of the book was ridiculously slow. The plot didn't pick up until about half way through. The characters didn't have a stand out personality. They seemed to be those kids that are hiden and shy. <br /><br />Gio, the alone teenage boy doesn't really understand the "liking" of the oposite sex, but when he meets Marisol, who in this case is lesbian, he falls in love. Giving the impression that he doesn't really know what he wants. Marisol is a bit confused as well. She knows that her preference is females, but now that she has met Gio feelings are changing. At first they give off the friendly vibes but after Marisol misses the bus home from a late night show and is forced to stay in Gio's bed things change. At the dance it all went horribly wrong when Gio makes the mistake of kissing her. This brings up the question, can a guy and a girl JUST be friends? <br /><br />The book doesnt really go in order in terms of order of events. It switches back and forth between families and friends. It also throws in the "zines" writen by young writers. They give a certain point of view about the characters. It throws you off in the begining but as you read throw understanding gets less complicated. </span>
  <a data-text-id="6493259908118891451" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

