<div id="review_382186685" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/382186685" />
    <a title="Lisa" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/1721945-lisa"><img alt="Lisa" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1343884078p2/1721945.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/382186685?book_show_action=true">Aug 01, 2012</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Lisa" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Lisa" href="/user/show/1721945-lisa">Lisa</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer382186685" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer10663247324157961690">Marisol has a lot to show John about how to write a good zine. And she’s fine with letting him and everyone else know she’s a lesbian--which isn’t a problem until he falls in love with her.<br/><br/>John’s voice feels very authentic, pouring out on the page what is hard for him to speak out loud. The layout of the book is engaging, with drawings and collages in the front pages, some paragraphs skewed at odd angles, handwritten notes and poems on lined paper, and excerpts from cut-and-paste xeroxed zines. </span>
  <span id="freeText10663247324157961690" style="display:none">Marisol has a lot to show John about how to write a good zine. And she’s fine with letting him and everyone else know she’s a lesbian--which isn’t a problem until he falls in love with her.<br /><br />John’s voice feels very authentic, pouring out on the page what is hard for him to speak out loud. The layout of the book is engaging, with drawings and collages in the front pages, some paragraphs skewed at odd angles, handwritten notes and poems on lined paper, and excerpts from cut-and-paste xeroxed zines. The story line is believable and not at all formulaic. This is an excellent book, with many facets for readers to relate to: the creative expression of the zine writers, John’s difficult relationships with his parents, Marisol’s outspoken expression of her sexuality, Diana’s gentle empathy, Brian and Emily finding each other through the school play, expressive song lyrics by Bob Franke and Ani diFranco, and settings in and around Boston and Cape Cod. All of it comes across as very real and alive. This is the kind of book that can help to affirm a reader’s own identity, whether gay or straight.</span>
  <a data-text-id="10663247324157961690" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


